{
  "text": "As an illustration, let us assume that the variability is constant across the visual field (for a given sensitivity level) [CITATION_1] with standard deviation r. /52; in other words, 25% higher. In reality, pointwise sensitivity and variability vary across the visual field, so the true increase in index variability caused by eccentricity weighting will not be as simple to calculate as in this example.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "17002540"
